The paper deals with communication complexity, which is a central topic in theoretical computer science and falls under the category of computational complexity (cs.CC). The use of multiplexing to combine messages sent in parallel executions of protocols is related to information theory (cs.IT). The paper also discusses the direct-sum problem, which is a well-studied problem in distributed computing and falls under the category of distributed systems (cs.DS). The formalization of sufficient conditions for communication complexity savings involves combinatorial and graph-theoretic arguments, which are typical of discrete mathematics (cs.DM). Finally, the paper mentions communication patterns, which are relevant to computational geometry (cs.CG) as well.
